  <h2>How We Identify Affiliate Links</h2>
  <p>Every article that contains affiliate links includes a <strong>disclosure notice</strong> at the top, reading:</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p><em>"This article contains affiliate links. We may earn a commission if you sign up through our links — at no extra cost to you."</em></p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>Individual affiliate links may also be marked with a note or labelled as "→ Try [Tool] free."</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Does This Affect Our Reviews?</h2>
  <p><strong>No.</strong> Our editorial process is independent of our affiliate relationships.</p>
  <p>Here is how we ensure this:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>We cover tools we would recommend regardless of commission.</strong> If a tool doesn't earn a commission but is the best option for a given use case, we say so.</li>
    <li><strong>We include genuine cons.</strong> Every review includes real limitations and situations where a tool is <em>not</em> the right choice — even when we earn a commission from it.</li>
    <li><strong>Commissions do not determine rankings.</strong> Our "best of" lists rank tools based on features, value, and use-case fit — not commission rate.</li>
    <li><strong>We disclose all affiliate relationships</strong> on every article that contains them.</li>
  </ol>

  <hr />

  <h2>FTC Compliance</h2>
  <p>This disclosure is made in compliance with the <strong>US Federal Trade Commission's guidelines</strong> concerning the use of endorsements and testimonials in advertising (16 CFR Part 255) and the <strong>UK Competition and Markets Authority's</strong> guidance on online reviews and endorsements.</p>

  <hr />

